content:
A dialog is the workhorse of your bot’s interaction with your customer.

Dialogs are conversation snippets that control what your bot can do. You can associate every dialog with a dialog intent which can be trained to understand variations in customer input. During a conversation with a customer, your bot moves between several different dialogs. Each dialog handles a portion of the conversation.

The following illustration gives you an overview of the Dialogs panel.

Add dialogs and groups as needed. The first dialog you present to your customer is the Welcome dialog. Use the action menu to set it to Welcome or Main Menu.

Design the way the dialog works by adding one or more of the following dialog steps:

* Outbound Messages: Displays an outgoing message from the bot to your customer.
* Questions: Gathers information from your customer.
* Actions: Performs an action on your Salesforce data.
* Rules: Perform specific tasks based on certain conditions.

To add a step to your dialog, drag a step from the Dialog Component Library onto the canvas. Configure the details in the Step Properties panel.

Name the dialog and decide whether to include it in the Bot Options menu that’s always available to your customers in the chat window. Set up a dialog by adding steps and telling the bot what to do after the dialog finishes. If you’re using intents, train the bot to understand the customer intent associated with the dialog.

Einstein Bots are built for conversation. To make setup a breeze, some of the most common dialogs are included with each new bot. These dialogs allow you to quickly transfer conversations to an agent, or gracefully end a chat.

You can use Map View to create a visual representation of how conversations move through your Einstein Bot.
title: Understanding Service Cloud and Einstein Bots
